TY  - JOUR
T1  - Organizational Culture: Can It Be a Source of Sustained Competitive Advantage?
AU  - Barney, Jay B.
Y1  - 1986/07/01
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1986.4306261
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1986.4306261
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 656
EP  - 665
VL  - 11
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Three attributes that a firm's culture must have to generate sustained competitive advantages are isolated. Previous findings suggest that the cultures of some firms have these attributes; thus, these cultures are a source of such advantages. The normative implications of the analysis are discussed. Firms that do not have the required cultures cannot engage in activities that will modify their cultures and generate sustained superior financial performance because their modified cultures typically will be neither rare nor imperfectly imitable. Firms that have cultures with the required attributes can obtain sustained superior financial performance from their cultures.
AB  - Three attributes that a firm's culture must have to generate sustained competitive advantages are isolated. Previous findings suggest that the cultures of some firms have these attributes; thus, these cultures are a source of such advantages. The normative implications of the analysis are discussed. Firms that do not have the required cultures cannot engage in activities that will modify their cultures and generate sustained superior financial performance because their modified cultures typically will be neither rare nor imperfectly imitable. Firms that have cultures with the required attributes can obtain sustained superior financial performance from their cultures.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1986.4306261
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1986.4306261
Y2  - 2026/04/24
