T1  - A Perceived Uncertainty Model of Human Resource Forecasting Technique Use
AU  - Stone, Thomas H.
AU  - Fiorito, Jack
Y1  - 1986/07/01
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1986.4306249
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1986.4306249
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 635
EP  - 642
VL  - 11
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A model of human resource forecasting (HRF) technique use is developed by integrating a perceived uncertainty component (Duncan, 1972) with Hogarth and Makridakis' (1981) model of human judgment. Predictions are generated from the model and existing literature is examined in support of the predictions. The authors conclude that their Perceived Uncertainty Model of Technique Use better explains use of HRF techniques than does a ?straight-line? evolutionary approach.
AB  - A model of human resource forecasting (HRF) technique use is developed by integrating a perceived uncertainty component (Duncan, 1972) with Hogarth and Makridakis' (1981) model of human judgment. Predictions are generated from the model and existing literature is examined in support of the predictions. The authors conclude that their Perceived Uncertainty Model of Technique Use better explains use of HRF techniques than does a ?straight-line? evolutionary approach.
